7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.04eed8bd-862b-4a05-9c1d-3b64c2b651ee.prompt=d64b020e-d3ca-47ce-9cf9-a65606679aad.82f33961-7bdc-42f4-af21-ed686fbd6db9.prompt 7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.05a34b2a-aa7e-424d-8a36-ded2545211cb.prompt=d64b020e-d3ca-47ce-9cf9-a65606679aad.5fad33c3-a363-4aff-b194-132d4a38a5d0.prompt 7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.0bb596f7-7917-4652-a5cb-9434dcdd2ea1.description=
Service to perform HTTP POST using the Java HTTP Client.

Inputs\:
    url - The URL where to send the HTTP POST request.
    username - The user name used for URL authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user'.
    password - The password used for URL authentication.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, springForm, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
    kerberosConfFile - The  path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty, the  (Key Distribution Center) and  get their values from the full domain name obtained from the web server URL.
    timeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in  milliseconds. This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A  value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyusername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy server.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the  input value.
    encodeURL - Specifies whether to encode the URL. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    file - The file to be posted by this operation using the HTTP POST method. This should be a path to a file/document on the disk.
    string - The raw text to be posted by this operation using the HTTP POST method.
    contentType - The content type that should be set in the request header, representing the MIME-type of the data in the message body.
Examples\: "text/html", "text/html; charset\=UTF-8", "application/x-www-form-urlencoded".
    characterSet - The character encoding of the text to be posted. If not specified this will be taken from the 'charset' field that can be specified in the  input. If the 'charset' field is absent, it will be set to 'ISO-8859-1' by default.
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used.
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file.
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used.
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file.
    headerNamesList - The list containing the header names to use for the request.
Example\: Accept,Content-Type
    headerValuesList - The list containing the header values to use for the request. 
Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
    queryNamesList - The list containing the names of the query parameters to use for the request. 
Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2 
    queryValuesList - The list containing the values of the query parameters to use for the request. 
Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
    delimiter - The delimiter used to separates list elements.
Default value\: ','

Results\: 
    returnCode - This is the primary output. A code used to determine the operation response, specifying whether the operation is successful or not.
    resultText - The raw result of the operation.
    document - The complete document returned by the Http Client Post Raw operation.
    URL - The URL used for the HTTP request.
    pageLoadTimeInMS - The number of milliseconds taken for the page to load.
    responseTimeInMS - The number of milliseconds taken before the server responded.
    errorMessage - An informational message that can help determine the cause of error, if an error occurred.
    httpResult - The descrition of the HTTP response returned by the web server for the request sent by this operation. This result contains the HTTP response status (for example, SUCCESS, PAGE_NOT_FOUND, UNAUTHORIZED, FORBIDDEN and so on) or GENERAL_ERROR if the HTTP request could not be executed.
    responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by .
    status - The HTTP response code.
Example\: HTTP/1.1 200 OK
    exception - If an error occurred, the stack trace of the thrown error.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    PAGE_NOT_FOUND - The URL specified to POST from was not found.
    INFORMATIONAL - The POST was not fully processed, the server responded with an informational response.
    REDIRECTION - The specified URL has moved.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
1. You can use KeyTool to import a SSL certificate in a KeyStore. For example, to import a certificate in the Java cacerts KeyStore, run\: keytool -import -file c\:/../.cer -alias  -keystore %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts -keystorepass changeit. If the KeyStore does not exist, the command tries to create a new one containing only your certificate.
2. You can use KeyTool to create a certificate chain through the following command\: 
   keytool -genkey -dname "cn\=Mark Jones, ou\=JavaSoft, o\=Sun, c\=US" 
      -alias business -keypass kpi135 -keystore C\:\working\mykeystore 
      -storepass ab987c -validity 180
It creates a certificate chain in a new keystore containing only one certificate.
3. If the value assigned to the  input is 'false' and  is empty, the operation tries to use the default trust store, using the password "changeit". 
4. If the authentication type is Kerberos, you might need to add an SPN (Service Principal Name) for the web server's computer account.  In order to do this, you can use ADUC (Active Directory Users and Computers) with enabled 'Advanced Features'. Go to the web server's computer account (example\: CN\=,CN\=Computers,DC\=domain,DC\=com), open the 'Properties' window and press the 'Attribute Editor' tab. Observe the values of the 'servicePrincipalName' attribute and add your SPN if not present. For example, HTTP/\:port.
5. If you need to specify query parameters when making the request, use the  and  inputs. The operation also accepts including query parameters in the URL. For example, http\://hostname\:80/page.asp?parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2. If you specify the same query parameter both through the  and the  inputs, the used value is the one from the , not the one included in the .
6. Apache Tomcat is currently the only supported application server when using form-based authentication.
7. This operation uses chunked transfer encoding, which may cause failures when using HTTP servers and proxies that do not support HTTP/1.1 protocol.
7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.0dfe352a-966f-4f1d-9730-ee17eaf9c240.description=
The operation invokes web service methods.  This operation should not be used directly\!  Please use the wizard to build flows that use this operation.

Inputs\:
    xmlTemplate - The template of the soap request to make.
    inputMap - A map used to map between template names and user-friendly names. The template names are pipe-delimited xpaths of the xmltemplate location, with a numerical element for lists.
Value format\: A list of elements separated by the new line delimiter. Eache element hes the format\: \=.
Example\: A line in the "inputMap" could be\: "Request|Details|0|Input|x\=input0.x"
    url - The url to Post to. 
    header_SOAPAction - The SOAPAction http header field, defined by many web services for indicating the intent of the request
    wswAuthenticationType - The authentication type to use for the "username" and "password" input.
Default value\: http
Valid values\: http, ntlm, ws-security digest, ws-security text
    WSSecuritySignRequest - Should the SOAP request be signed using WS-Security.
Default value\: false
Valid values true, false
    WSSecurityEncryptRequest - Should the entire SOAP request be signed using WS-Security.
Default value\: false
Valid values true, false
    WSSecurityTimestampRequest - Should the Timestamp attribute be added to the WS-Security header
Default value\: false
Valid values true, false
    WSSecurityKeystore - Keystore to use for encrypting and signing requests.
    WSSecurityKeystoreType - The type of "WSSecurityKeystore".
    WSSecurityKeystorePassword - The password for "WSSecurityKeystore".
    contentType - Value to be used in the Content-Type HTTP header.
Default value\: text/xml
    characterSet - The character set for HTTP Get request and response.
Default value\: UTF-8
    username - The username to use for authenticating with the web service.
Value format\: For NTLM authentication, the required format is domain\user.
    password - The password to use for authenticating with the web service.
    trustAllRoots - Enables weak security over SSL. A SSH certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    usesJSON - Use JSON arrays for the SOAP Request for all Array types.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    timeout - a timeout after which the connection should be terminated or 0 for no timeout.
    socketTimeout - The time to wait for data to be retrieved, in milliseconds. This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    proxy - A proxy to use when accessing the web service.
    proxyPort - A port on the proxy to connect to.
    proxyUsername - A username to use when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - A password to use when connecting to the proxy.
    keystore - The path to the keystore to use for SSL Client Certificates when using http authentication.
    keystorePassword - The password for the keystore when using http authentication.
    ICONCLUDE_WSW_VERSION - This value is used internally by the operation.
    returnXMLRequest - If this input is set to true, a new output named "rawXMLRequest" is returned from the operation which contains the text of the SOAP request that will be sent. This can be very valuable in troubleshooting.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false

Results\:
    returnCode - This is the primary output. It contains the value 0 if the operation successfully completes and the value -1 otherwise.
    document - Raw XML response.
    documentStripped - Raw XML response stripped of namespaces for ease in parsing with XML XPath operations.
    jsonStripped - Raw XML response stripped of namespaces for ease in parsing with JSON operations, input usesJSON must be set to true for this to be populated.

Responses\:
    success - SOAP request completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Notes\:
1.If wswAuthenticationType\=ws-security text then this operation transmits passwords in clear-text.
2.Any additional inputs that follow these are added by the Web Service Wizard, and they are specific to the particular web service method being called.
3.If you add new step-level inputs with the name header_, where  is the name of an html header, then that html header will be set to the given value in the HTTP request.
4.This operation will not allow connection through secure transport layers below TLS 1.0.
7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.0f29aec1-002c-42f4-95c0-cb0ebcc8e845.prompt=d64b020e-d3ca-47ce-9cf9-a65606679aad.2715c46d-ca90-44d9-ad8d-ed5ba8f081fc.prompt 7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.286d5d65-0105-4c2a-96cf-8d33f7f7cedd.description=
Runs a SQL command against an Oracle database, using the information available in the tnsnames.ora file.   
Does not return any results (only whether the command was executed)

Input Parameters\:
TNSPath - The path to the parent folder of the TNS file which contains the DB connecting info(the name of the DB server, the port used for connecting to the DB server, the database name)
TNSEntry - the entry name from the tnsnames.ora file which contains the connecting information
Username - username to connect as
Password - password
Command - the command to execute

Responses\:
more items - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
updateCount - the update count of the command executed

NOTE\: 
This op supports only Oracle. The tnsnames.ora file should correctly configured on the RAS machine.

ORACLE NOTE\:
It is possible to run PL/SQL procedures using this operation. The examples below present the syntax to be used for having the same effect as the following PL/SQL script\:
BEGIN
  send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');
END;

Example 1\: BEGIN send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');END;

Example 2\: BEGIN send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test');END;

Example 3\: {CALL send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test')}

Example 4\: {CALL send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test')}
7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.308348fc-db93-4860-8e67-adedfc9bd67e.prompt=70b893d6-e51e-4763-82b7-4387620e9de1.04e6f5c5-a060-4159-90d6-56dd66b0c2d1.prompt 7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.34267dd3-262e-4a90-8653-9a1d3b7c5b2f.prompt=70b893d6-e51e-4763-82b7-4387620e9de1.0ce5f99d-6acf-4904-9c04-1587e4685ee5.prompt 7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.34ab9a92-099a-421f-9d66-8fe23f2c4e66.description=
Check the current date and time, and returns a java DateAndTime formatted string of it. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale.Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. 
Examples\:  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Result\:
    Current date and time.

Responses\:
    success - Date/time retrieved successfully.   
    failure - Date/time could not be retrieved.

Notes.
    1. If localeLang is 'unix' the localeCountry input is ignored and the result will be the current UNIX timestamp.

7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.8a097706-a947-4d67-804b-ffbbd07a2148.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
    string1 - The first string. 
Default value\: "" (empty)
    string2 - The second string.
Default value\: "" (empty)
    ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

Responses\:
    true - If the two strings are equal.
    false - If the two strings are not equal.

7d5eb700-758e-41e8-a50f-43c485137399.93da5e82-f665-45fe-a80a-e9e667ce7f82.description=
Sends an smtp email
 
Input Parameters\:
hostname - hostname or ip address of smtp server
port - port smtp service is listening
from - from email address
to - email address(s) or recipients
subject - email subject
body - body of the email
htmlEmail - true or false, whether the email should be sent supporting html rich email.
readReceipt - true or false, whether or not to request a read receipt
attachments - comma separated list of files to attach (must be full path)
username - if SMTP authentication is needed, the username to send
password - the password to use
characterSet - the character set encoding for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is UTF-8
contentTransferEncoding - the content transfer encoding scheme (such as 7bit, 8bit, base64, quoted-printable etc) for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is - quoted-printable or Q Encoding.
 
 Responses\:
 success - successfully sent the email
 failure - failed to send the email

Note\:
For special characters (East Asian, right-to-left languages, etc.) you must install the support files on your local machine.
	For doing this on Windows go to Control Panel -> Regional and Language Options -> Language and check the options at Supplemental language support.
